<Introduction to the Course>
oooo
0000
Why take this course?
• You will understand the principles behind web application
development
• Not simply copy-paste code from websites to string together a
web application
• You will understand why technologies are the way they are,
rather than accept it as a statement of fact, and perhaps
change them if needed
• It enables you to design novel techniques and technologies in
the web application space
If you put in the effort, this course will be really fun! :-)

<Introduction to the Course>

Why not to take this course?
OOOOO
You just want to write a (lot of) web code
• Online tutorials will teach you how to do this
• While you'll do a series of programming assignments, their
focus is to teach you the principles
want to impress your future employer with cool-sounding
buzzwords
• There won't be many of these unfortunately
• You want an easy final year elective course
• This course will require significant work. It will not be easy.

<Introduction to the Course>

000
Pre-requisites
• EECE 210 or equivalent (e.g., CPSC 210)
• Principles of software development
• Knowledge of invariants, specifications etc.
• Experience using at least one OOP language (e.g., Java)
● Maturity to tackle large software development tasks
● No Web programming/JavaScript experience is needed
• However, you should be able to pick it up quickly
• Invest considerable time outside of class in learning JavaScript

● Assignments (40%): Five programming assignments worth 8%

Assignments
• Five Assignments where you'll build a complete web
application from scratch (i.e., chat server and client)
• Assignments build cumulatively on each other. Missing even
one assignment means you'll lose big !
• Solutions will not be provided for any of the assignments - use
your own code from prev. assignments
To be done individually; No collaboration allowed with anyone
(even for ideas)
• Submission via Github (later) - physical presence not needed in
the lab

Exams & Quizzes
• One mid-term exam and one final exam (cumulative).
Distribution is as follows:
Midterm: 13% (November 2nd)
• Final exam: 25% (in December)
• Quizzes almost every week: 12% (1% per quiz)
Exams and Quizzes are open-book, open notes. But

All exams will be done online on Hacker Rank there's no

Programming Proficiency Quiz
● Will test you on basics of JavaScript (Sep 20th): Self-study
• 5 programming problems of 1 mark each - involving basic
JavaScript coding
• Needs to pass provided all test cases for each program. No
partial credits.
• To be taken online during the class time on Sep 20th on
HackerRank platform
• Start preparing for the test now. Will release practice test by
the weekend.
• We don't care about code quality though. Instantaneous
feedback and results.
• Your score is WYSIWG- provided you don't hard-code for test
cases (you'll get 0 if so)

<Introduction to the Course>

Final Thoughts
• Do you really want to take this course ?
• Involves significant amount of work and time
• Easier electives are available in your final year
• Requires spending time outside of class hours
• If you're staying, welcome on board !
• This is the eighth time this course is being offered (seventh
time I'm offerring it)
Significant changes this time based on feedback from previous
years
• So please feel free to give us suggestions for improvement
(these are actively encouraged)
• Tell us what you liked and what you didn't like - we've
incorporated past suggestions.
